# ng -- "netstat grep": show network connections/sockets whose lines match a
# pattern, while always keeping netstat's header row so the columns make sense.
#
# What it does: runs `netstat -anp` (all sockets, numeric addresses, with the
# owning program), prints the first line (the column header), then prints only
# the lines matching the pattern you pass as the first argument.
#
# How to run it:
#   ng <pattern>        e.g.  ng :443        ng sshd        ng LISTEN
# (No shebang; run via `sh ng <pattern>` or make it executable. Needs sudo,
#  which is invoked inside, so it may prompt for a password.)
#
# Prerequisites: netstat (from net-tools), egrep, sudo.

# Build a unique temp filename. $$ is the current shell's process ID, so two
# runs won't clash. The leading dot just makes it a hidden file in /tmp.
tmpfile=/tmp/.grep.$$
# Create/empty that file ('>' with no command truncates it to zero length).
>$tmpfile

# Capture the full netstat output into the temp file (needs root to see the
# program name/PID for every socket, hence sudo).
#   -a all sockets   -n numeric (no DNS/port-name lookups)   -p show program
sudo netstat -anp > $tmpfile
# Print line 1 only: the column header (Proto, Local Address, State, etc.).
head -1 $tmpfile
# Print every line that matches the user's pattern ($1). egrep = grep -E
# (extended regular expressions).
egrep $1 $tmpfile

# Clean up the temp file.
rm $tmpfile
